rty)."]}]},{"name":"Nevers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: habitational name from the city of Nevers in France.","Possibly an altered form of English   Nevard   or perhaps of its extinct variant <b>Neverd</b>. The surname <i>Nevers</i> is also found in Jamaica.","History: The majority of the American bearers of this surname trace their origin to Richard Nevers, born in 1666 in Woburn, MA. His origin is not known, but his surname is also documented in the forms <i>Nevard</i> and <i>Neverds</i>, which make it possible that Richard Nevers was of English origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevard","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Nevard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Niwhard</i>, from <i>niw-</i> ‘new’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘strong, hardy’. Compare   Nevers  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Nevers V, Comte de Nevers et d'Auxerre was born in 1150, in Nevers, Nièvre, Burgundy, France, his father, Guillaume de Nevers, was 122 and his mother, Ida Von Sponheim, Comtess de Nevers et d'Auxerre et Tonnerre, was 27. He marr